    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Retrieving the Recyclables: Workers Pick Up Where New Yorkers Leave Off'' (news article, June 27):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Retrieving the Recyclables: Workers Pick Up Where New Yorkers Leave Off'' (news article, June 27):</p>
        <p>Yard waste adds 5 to 15 percent or more to recycling rates in less densely populated cities, so that New York's 20 percent residential recycling rate without yard waste is a substantial achievement.</p>
        <p>The numbers cited in your article for Portland, Ore., and Minneapolis are not confined to their residential recycling programs but include the commercial sector as well. When commercial recycling is included, the recycling rate for New York City is more than 55 percent.</p>
        <p>ROBERT LANGE  Dir., Bureau of Waste Prevention,  Reuse and Recycling  Department of Sanitation  New York, June 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
